    "body": "### Problem\n\n* **Description:** Pressing `Enter`, `Backspace`, or `Tab` in Neovim triggers the action twice.\n* **Behavior:** The input is registered once on **key press** and again on **key release** (verifiable by pressing and holding the key slowly).\n* **Environment:**\n    * Occurs in the **Kitty terminal**, regardless of whether `$TERM` is set to `xterm-256color` or `xterm-kitty`.\n    * The system uses the **kime** input method.\n* **Troubleshooting & Scope:**\n    * **`kitty +kitten show_key`** confirms that the terminal sends only a single sequence per keystroke.\n    * The issue persists even when running with `nvim --clean`.\n    * Running `printf \"\\x1b[>0u\" && nvim --clean` does not resolve the issue.\n    * The problem is also present within Neovim's `:terminal`.\n    * **Regression:** This issue **does not occur** in Neovim 0.9.x.\n\n---\n*This issue report was drafted with the assistance of AI to ensure clarity and technical accuracy.*\n\n---\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Open Kitty terminal.\n2. Run `nvim --clean`.\n3. Enter Insert mode (`i`).\n4. Press and hold `Enter` -> One newline appears.\n5. Release `Enter` -> A second newline appears immediately.\n\nthis is my init.vim file\n[init.vim.txt](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/26560558/init.vim.txt)\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nNo input when key release.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.12.0 Release\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.1\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nlinux mint Cinnamon/22.3\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nkitty/0.32.2\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color or xterm-kitty\n\n### Installation\n\nDownload and extract tar.gz package from github.com release page.",
